\begin_layout Section
Discrimination of Signal and Background
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For multivariant classification, input variables have to be pict from the
 event kinematics.
 The choice for a certain variable is often made according to its significance
 within the multivariant training phase.
 This is case if one is solely interested in the highest discrimination
 power with a minimum set of variables.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For this analyses it is crucial to minimalize the bias on the shape of the
 observables after a discriminator is applied.
 This requirement can be met by choosing non-correlated variables which
 maybe independent to the observables.
 The actual influence however is investigated by the anomalous coupling
 samples.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Choice of Independent Variables
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One way of estimating a correlation between two variables is provided by
 the Pearson product-moment correlation coefficient.
 It is calculated between the variables 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
r=\frac{\sum_{i}\left(x_{i}-\bar{x}\right)\left(y_{i}-\bar{y}\right)}{\sqrt{\sum_{i}\left(x_{i}-\bar{x}\right)^{2}}\sqrt{\sum_{i}\left(y_{i}-\bar{y}\right)^{2}}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{y}$
\end_inset

 are the means of the respective distributions.
 It is however only sensitive to a linear dependence between two variables.
 To detect even non-linear dependencies a more sophisticated method has
 to be applied.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An algorithm to test an independence hypothesis has been proposed by utilizing
 a 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi^{2}$
\end_inset

-test 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "independentAlgo"

\end_inset

.
 The algorithm is composed in two steps.
 Suppose the distributions 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 are subjected to testing for independence between them.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First, the distributions of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 are flattend.
 This is performed by constructing a copula in which 
\begin_inset Formula $x\rightarrow\tilde{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y\rightarrow\tilde{y}$
\end_inset

 are only within the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{x},\,\tilde{y}\in[0;\,1]$
\end_inset

.
 For a finite amount 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,\, y)$
\end_inset

 pairs this can be done by sorting 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}=(x_{1},\ldots x_{N})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{y}=(y_{1},\ldots y_{N})$
\end_inset

 independently and reasigning their values according to the positions after
 the sorting
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
x_{i}^{\mathrm{sorted}}\rightarrow\tilde{x}_{i}\equiv\frac{i}{N},\quad y_{i}^{\mathrm{sorted}}\rightarrow\tilde{y}_{i}\equiv\frac{i}{N}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Second, from the flattend distributions an 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times n$
\end_inset

 histogram 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 with equidistant binning is created.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 are independent, then the histogram content is expected to be compatible
 with a 2d uniformed distribution.
 To quantify the hypothesis a 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi^{2}$
\end_inset

-test by calculating
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\chi^{2}=\sum_{i}\sum_{j}\frac{\left(h_{ij}-e\right)^{2}}{\sigma_{e}^{2}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

with the expectation value and its uncertainty
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
e=\frac{N}{n^{2}},\qquad\sigma_{e}=\sqrt{\frac{N}{n^{2}}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

is performed.
 The probability of the flat hypothese follows a 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi^{2}$
\end_inset

-distribution with 
\begin_inset Formula $n^{2}-(2n-1)$
\end_inset

 degrees of freedom.
 The additional 
\begin_inset Formula $2n-1$
\end_inset

 degrees of freedom are not present due to the copula transformation in
 the first step.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This algorithms has been fed with over 700 different variables, including
 basic kinematics of one reconstructed particle and correlated variables
 like 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta p_{\mathrm{T}}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\phi$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta R$
\end_inset

, angles and invariant masses between two particles which are defined during
 the top quark event reconstruction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Confidence was gained in the algorithm as it first suggested the 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 angles of all particles which are expected to be independent to any other
 kinematic variable due to the detector geometry.
 But these angles do not support any discrimination power between signal
 and background processes and are therefore neglected in the variable choice.
\end_layout

