\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

Large oscillations appear if one tries to unfold another distribution with
 an inverted response matrix.
 Those oscillations can already arise through statistical fluctuations.
 To understand this behavior the Singular Value Decomposition (SVD) provides
 more insight.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
SVD can be used to decompose even non-quadratic matrices 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 into the form
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
A=U\cdot D\cdot V
\end{equation}

\end_inset

with the diagonal matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

.
 The diagonal elements 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{ii}$
\end_inset

 are called singular values.
 They are per convention normalized as 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{11}=1$
\end_inset

 and sorted as 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{ii}>D_{i+1,\, i+1}$
\end_inset

.
 To provide a simple example, the response matrix 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
A=\frac{1}{2}\cdot\left(\begin{array}{cc}
1+\epsilon & 1-\epsilon\\
1-\epsilon & 1+\epsilon
\end{array}\right),\qquad\epsilon\in[0;\,1]
\end{equation}

\end_inset

from a fictitious detector with the parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset

 shall be analyzed.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset

 goes to 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 the detector can measure a variable in both bins unmistakable.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

 both bins get more smeared until they are not more distinguishable by the
 detector.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The SVD decomposition applied to 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 leads to the solution
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\vec{x} & =\underbrace{\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\left(\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 1\\
1 & -1
\end{array}\right)}_{=U^{-1}}\cdot\underbrace{\left(\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 0\\
0 & {\textstyle \frac{1}{\epsilon}}
\end{array}\right)}_{=D^{-1}}\cdot\underbrace{\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\left(\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 1\\
1 & -1
\end{array}\right)}_{=V^{-1}}\cdot\left(\begin{array}{c}
y_{1}\\
y_{2}
\end{array}\right)\\
 & =\underbrace{1}_{D_{11}^{-1}}\cdot\frac{1}{2}\left(\begin{array}{c}
1\\
1
\end{array}\right)\cdot\left(y_{1}+y_{2}\right)+\underbrace{\frac{1}{\epsilon}}_{D_{22}^{-1}}\cdot\frac{1}{2}\underbrace{\left(\begin{array}{c}
1\\
-1
\end{array}\right)}_{\mathrm{anti\, correlation}}\cdot\left(y_{1}-y_{2}\right)\label{eq:anticorr}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
for the unfolding problem.
 The last term in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:anticorr"

\end_inset

 induces an anticorrelation between 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 If the singular value 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{22}$
\end_inset

 goes to zero, this leads to oscillations.
 The oscillation term dominates through the sorting of the SVDs 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{ii}>D_{i+1,\, i+1}$
\end_inset

 the first term in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:anticorr"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In conclusion, this means that differences between two bins get unphysically
 amplified through simple inversion if the response matrix contains very
 small singular values.
 For a tradeoff between unphysical fluctuations and physical meaning the
 singular values need to be regularized.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Regularization
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The simplest regularization method is realized by performing a singular
 value decomposition of the response matrix and dropping a certain amount
 of SVDs during the matrix inversion.
 This method is often called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

SVD Unfolding
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 The regularization can be referred to as a hard cut off 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau<n$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x_{i}=\left(\sum_{j}^{\tau}U_{ij}^{-1}\frac{1}{D_{jj}}V_{ji}^{-1}x_{j}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

