\begin_layout Standard
Another regularization method can be performed by suppressing large fluctuations
 explicitly through a 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi^{2}-\mathrm{fit}$
\end_inset

.
 The unfolded distribution is found by minimizing the function
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\chi^{2}=\left(\vec{y}-A\vec{x}\right)^{\mathrm{T}}\cdot V_{yy}^{-1}\cdot\left(\vec{y}-A\vec{x}\right)+\mathrm{optional\, terms},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{yy}$
\end_inset

 denotes the covariance matrix of 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{y}$
\end_inset

.
 If the measured distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{y}$
\end_inset

 contains no correlations between its bins the covariance matrix can be
 expressed as 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{jj}=\sqrt{y_{j}}$
\end_inset

 which assumes Poisson uncertainties.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To suppress large fluctuations as optional term 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
+\tau^{2}\vec{x}\cdot L^{\mathrm{T}}L\cdot\vec{x}+\left(\sum y_{i}-\epsilon^{\mathrm{T}}\vec{x}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

